WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.070 --> 00:00:01.040
MATTEO VALLONE: My
name is Matteo Vallone,

00:00:01.040 --> 00:00:03.690
and I work in apps and games
business development team.

00:00:03.690 --> 00:00:07.190
And in my day to day job I
work with both apps and games

00:00:07.190 --> 00:00:07.992
developers.

00:00:07.992 --> 00:00:09.825
So I thought it would
be interesting for you

00:00:09.825 --> 00:00:11.430
as app developers
to learn more about

00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:15.130
what successful games
developers care about.

00:00:15.130 --> 00:00:21.650
And not only that, I will
try to extrapolate some rules

00:00:21.650 --> 00:00:23.530
that you can apply in
your day to day job.

00:00:23.530 --> 00:00:25.590
And, also, I will
show some examples

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:29.450
of how these rules have been
applied by apps developers.

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:35.410
But before that I want to spend
some time talking about why

00:00:35.410 --> 00:00:37.480
we think games and
apps should learn

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:40.320
from each other-- what are
the relevant things that they

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:42.230
have in common.

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:44.820
But I don't want to
oversimplify this.

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:47.140
Actually, I want to address
the elephant in the room

00:00:47.140 --> 00:00:48.020
right away.

00:00:48.020 --> 00:00:50.760
It's much more difficult to
make money on apps than games.

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:51.750
We all know that.

00:00:51.750 --> 00:00:54.590
And it's not only because
it's generally more accepted

00:00:54.590 --> 00:00:57.960
to pay for games than apps,
but also because games

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:00.450
have much more flexibility
in their mechanics

00:01:00.450 --> 00:01:03.460
and what they can do to
actually monetize users.

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:05.870
They're also selling
virtual goods.

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:08.280
So there's endless
possibilities what they can sell

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:10.606
and the price points
they can put together.

00:01:10.606 --> 00:01:11.980
So they basically
can do whatever

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:15.270
they want in terms of
selling virtual currencies

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:18.220
or virtual goods in a game.

00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:21.790
For apps that's not possible.

00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:24.430
But the math is always the same.

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:27.310
Apps and games, in
both cases, the model--

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:30.220
the dominant model--
is the freemium model.

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:32.490
That means that this
equation on the right

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:34.740
here, that is always true.

00:01:34.740 --> 00:01:38.140
CPI, cost per install,
for your installs

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:41.570
should always be lower than
the lifetime value of the users

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:43.260
that you're bringing in.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:45.730
And that means that
in a world where

00:01:45.730 --> 00:01:47.560
CPI is rising
because there's more

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:50.670
competition for servicability,
for user acquisition,

00:01:50.670 --> 00:01:53.200
in order to make
this function work

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:56.990
you really need to focus on the
right side of this equation.

00:01:56.990 --> 00:02:01.150
And lifetime value is a function
of retention, engagement,

00:02:01.150 --> 00:02:03.310
and conversion,
and monetization.

00:02:03.310 --> 00:02:06.100
But it all starts with
retention because that's

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:07.840
what drives engagement.

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:09.880
That's a measure of
engagement, and that's

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:11.526
what drives monetization.

00:02:11.526 --> 00:02:14.770
So retention is king.

00:02:14.770 --> 00:02:18.790
This data from a mobile
intelligence company, Quettra,

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:23.190
show how, actually, this is
so important for both apps

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:24.120
and games.

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:27.640
Here you see a comparison
of retention curves of apps

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:30.700
based on Google
Play Store ranking.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:33.600
Here you see that the top
games and the top apps,

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:37.140
they all have better
retention than the ones below.

00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:40.570
So even if the curves are
a little bit different,

00:02:40.570 --> 00:02:44.030
games tend to have
shorter term retention

00:02:44.030 --> 00:02:47.120
because they are less-- they
have less longevity than apps.

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:49.060
In general this is always true.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:51.079
So it's not only something
that games developers

00:02:51.079 --> 00:02:52.870
should care about--
also apps should really

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:55.400
care about retention.

00:02:55.400 --> 00:03:00.100
And going a bit further in
retention, the key metric

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.540
that you should
look at when you try

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:04.850
to optimize your
long-term retention

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:09.570
is frequency, because
that shows how many times

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:11.540
a user comes back to your app.

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:14.010
If users come back
to your app often,

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:16.010
chances are they will
get hooked by it.

00:03:16.010 --> 00:03:18.710
They will make it part
of their daily routine.

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:21.500
That means they will be retained
and they will become your users

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:23.770
forever, hopefully.

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:27.390
This graphic shows
how different apps

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:31.010
category and games
genre have-- they

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:32.379
are mapped along two metrics.

00:03:32.379 --> 00:03:34.420
One is the frequency per
week-- so how many times

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:37.650
a user visits on average
those apps in a week.

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:40.410
And the day 90 retention--
so the long-term retention,

00:03:40.410 --> 00:03:42.810
the end of that curve
that I showed before.

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:46.220
You see that, while they are
different-- it depends on where

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:48.730
you are in this category--
there is a direct correlation

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:50.750
between the two.

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:51.420
All right.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:52.530
So retention is king.

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:55.340
And games know this very well.

00:03:55.340 --> 00:03:57.480
They spend a lot of time
optimizing for that,

00:03:57.480 --> 00:03:58.554
and you see how--

00:03:58.554 --> 00:03:59.220
[AUDIO PLAYBACK]

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:00.303
-The icon needs to appeal.

00:04:00.303 --> 00:04:01.704
[END PLAYBACK]

00:04:01.704 --> 00:04:03.150
MATTEO VALLONE: Sorry.

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:07.360
You see how pretty much every
successful game developer--

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:10.490
and there are a few
highlighted here--

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:14.330
they tend to before launching
a new game to the public,

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:16.190
they do what we
call soft launching.

00:04:16.190 --> 00:04:19.050
They pick a test market
or a beta community,

00:04:19.050 --> 00:04:21.779
and they spend a lot of
time optimizing their game,

00:04:21.779 --> 00:04:24.920
tweaking it to the point where
the retention figures are

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:25.910
satisfactory.

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:28.660
And this process requires
a lot of discipline.

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:31.780
A lot of games get killed
during this process.

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:34.680
But it also ensures that
they invest resources

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:38.000
in the right product that
actually has a chance

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.920
to be successful and
where that equation

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:43.410
that I showed you before works.

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:45.540
If you don't do this
already, retention

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:48.280
can be measured very easily
through Google Play-- so sorry,

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:49.592
through Google Analytics.

00:04:49.592 --> 00:04:51.050
And this is the
report that you can

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:54.020
look at that shows on the
top, your retention curve.

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:56.200
This is your app
retention curve.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:59.870
And also, it shows a
breakdown of retention figures

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:03.170
by cores of users that install
the app in a given day.

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:09.070
So you can also optimize and
see how it impacts retention.

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:09.570
All right.

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:11.160
So now let's talk
about some things

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:13.640
that you can actually
learn from the games world

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:16.990
and apply in your
day to day job.

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:19.960
The first one is focusing
on engagement cliff.

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:21.360
This is very important.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:26.080
And I'm showing you again the
chart with retention figures

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:29.330
because there's something
else that can be noted here.

00:05:29.330 --> 00:05:33.060
You see how in each
case regardless

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:36.590
of how successful the
app is, most of the users

00:05:36.590 --> 00:05:38.870
are lost in the
first seven days.

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:40.890
That's where everyone loses.

00:05:40.890 --> 00:05:43.910
And actually, the
top apps are the ones

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:45.940
that are doing a
better job, especially

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:47.650
in the first seven days.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:50.930
After that the curves tend
to flatten for everyone,

00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:53.740
so there's not much difference
between different apps.

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:55.700
But those first seven
days are critical.

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:59.080
Here you see on the right an
average day seven retention.

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:01.210
So after those seven
days, how many users

00:06:01.210 --> 00:06:04.020
are still in the app
for different categories

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:04.630
on average.

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:06.950
Again, this is Quettra data.

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:11.340
And you see how it varies
between 40% and 15%.

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:16.610
That means that, on
average, 60% to 85% of users

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:18.630
are lost in those
first seven days.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:22.809
And that's because users
need to try an app.

00:06:22.809 --> 00:06:24.850
They install a lot of
apps, but then they try it.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:26.850
And in those first few
days they actually decide

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:30.410
whether they want to still use
it, or just leave it there.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:33.140
Once they decide, once
the app is good enough,

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:34.980
then chances are the
users will stick.

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:37.820
And actually, that's why
the curves flattens here.

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:40.860
But those first seven
days are critical.

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:42.310
Games know this very well.

00:06:42.310 --> 00:06:44.740
In a game onboarding
is quite challenging.

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:48.280
You have to teach a user new
rules, new mechanics, why

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:51.260
you should care, what is
the story, lots of things.

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:52.720
So it all starts
with a tutorial.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:55.800
And I want to show you
an excerpt of a video

00:06:55.800 --> 00:06:58.460
that we recently shot with
a very successful game

00:06:58.460 --> 00:07:02.770
developer called Pixelberry
that has a great completion

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:04.140
rate for its tutorial.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:07.020
70% of people that
actually start a tutorial

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:10.160
go through each section
of the tutorial.

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:12.384
So let's play the video
and we'll comment that.

00:07:12.384 --> 00:07:13.050
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:13.050 --> 00:07:16.380
-Players coming in, we hit
them with story right away.

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:19.120
And we try and do
it in a way where

00:07:19.120 --> 00:07:20.420
it's a little more natural.

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:23.020
We are cognizant that a
lot of people playing games

00:07:23.020 --> 00:07:26.190
on mobile phones may not
want to read too much text,

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:29.620
so we try to ease
players into that.

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:32.190
But by the time they
finish our tutorial,

00:07:32.190 --> 00:07:34.060
we're hoping that
they're already caught up

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:35.370
in the lives of these
characters and they

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:37.161
want to learn more
about their back stories

00:07:37.161 --> 00:07:38.190
and what's going on.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.466
-I think it is
important to give people

00:07:40.466 --> 00:07:41.840
kind of that sense
of progression

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:43.840
in a game-- especially
in mobile games.

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:45.754
Because I think that
in a lot of games

00:07:45.754 --> 00:07:47.920
that you can reach a certain
point where you're just

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:50.740
repeating the same actions, and
you want to feel like you're

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:51.905
doing something different.

00:07:51.905 --> 00:07:54.030
And I think story is a
great way of differentiating

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:56.940
that and saying, oh, now you're
dealing with a new villain,

00:07:56.940 --> 00:07:59.207
or now you're dealing with
a new issue that's come up.

00:07:59.207 --> 00:07:59.790
[END PLAYBACK]

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:02.520
MATTEO VALLONE: So they
talk about two key things.

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:04.810
One is the story-- they
use story to hook players

00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:06.780
right away, and
they rely on that

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.580
to make sure that it's
compelling for the user

00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:11.660
to stick around for
the whole tutorial.

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:13.887
The other thing they talk
about is progression.

00:08:13.887 --> 00:08:15.470
Progression is very
important in games

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:18.380
because, if you think about it,
the game is always presenting

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:19.490
you with a new challenge.

00:08:19.490 --> 00:08:21.260
If you get a sense
of progression,

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:24.180
you keep playing the game--
otherwise it gets boring.

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:26.222
Those challenges shouldn't
be too challenging,

00:08:26.222 --> 00:08:27.430
otherwise you leave the game.

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:29.180
So it's always finding
the right balance

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:33.460
between making you stick around
to play the next challenge,

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.750
but it's not too
difficult for you.

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:39.020
And I actually want to show
you this concept of progression

00:08:39.020 --> 00:08:41.970
and onboarding goes beyond a
tutorial with the other example

00:08:41.970 --> 00:08:45.220
of Playdots, another very
successful game developer.

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:47.930
This is a chart that
shows all their levels.

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:49.650
They are mapped
along two metrics--

00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:52.250
one is revenue per
player in that level,

00:08:52.250 --> 00:08:56.640
and lapse rate-- how many people
left the game in that level.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:00.640
By tweaking the difficulty
level and the experience

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:02.940
in the levels that are
below the red lines,

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:05.170
for the under-performing
ones, they actually

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:08.380
managed to improve
not only retention

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:11.270
but also average
revenue per paying user.

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:13.400
So again, the message
here is-- this

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:15.590
is very specific to
games, of course--

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:18.110
but the message is it's not
only about the tutorial,

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:21.060
it's about how you
communicate and foster a sense

00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:24.310
of progression within the game.

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:24.810
OK.

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:30.780
Let's try to extrapolate
some rules for apps now.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.020
The important thing here is
that in the first seven days

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:35.680
there is an engagement cliff.

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:37.680
The user is presented
with a new app.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:40.980
They have to understand how it
works and start playing with it

00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:42.200
and understand the value.

00:09:42.200 --> 00:09:44.620
And you want to ease that
cliff as much as possible

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:47.050
to help them going
through those seven days

00:09:47.050 --> 00:09:51.260
to the point where they
will probably stick around.

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:52.940
So the first thing
to do is finding

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:56.307
features that provide
value to the user

00:09:56.307 --> 00:09:58.390
without asking much from
them-- something that you

00:09:58.390 --> 00:10:02.430
can show them and they
can experience right away.

00:10:02.430 --> 00:10:04.640
And after that you need to
understand the activation

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:05.140
moments.

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:08.600
What are the key things that
you want the user to do in order

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:12.120
to fully experience your app and
that requires some engagement

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:12.980
some commitment?

00:10:12.980 --> 00:10:15.970
For example, creating an
account, uploading a video,

00:10:15.970 --> 00:10:19.410
finding some friends, adding
some preferences-- something

00:10:19.410 --> 00:10:22.800
that personalizes and
makes the experience deeper

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:25.470
but requires also some
actions from the user.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:27.940
And you should present
those things gradually.

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:30.280
You should help them going
through each one of them

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:33.450
step by step instead
of overwhelming them

00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:36.910
with everything
at the same time.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:38.500
As a consequence,
also, part of that

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:41.430
is that you should manage
the appearance of pay walls,

00:10:41.430 --> 00:10:43.450
especially in those
first few days.

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:46.480
You don't want to scare
people off or overwhelm them

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:48.990
with the requirements.

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:51.270
So that's the general rule.

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:53.470
And something that can
help you optimizing

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:57.130
your app along this
rule is the flow report

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:58.140
in Google Analytics.

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:01.070
This shows you how
users, on average,

00:11:01.070 --> 00:11:03.940
move between different
screens in your app.

00:11:03.940 --> 00:11:05.750
You can see the path they take.

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:08.640
And more importantly,
with the red lines here

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:12.252
you can see where they
get out of the app.

00:11:12.252 --> 00:11:13.460
What are the friction points?

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:14.620
What are the roadblocks?

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:17.790
And potentially remove some
of them, if it makes sense.

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:19.880
So very useful report to use.

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:24.040
And I want to show you
an example of an app that

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:26.860
did a great job applying
these rules recently

00:11:26.860 --> 00:11:28.990
when they redesigned
their own boarding flow.

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:32.320
Overall they achieved
20% better day

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:35.170
seven retention, which
is a great figure.

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:38.020
The way they did it is that--
first of all, let's talk

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:39.700
about dating sites and apps.

00:11:39.700 --> 00:11:44.760
They require a lot of things to
set up before you can actually

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:46.720
enjoy and use that dating app.

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:48.020
You have to create an account.

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:49.811
You have to write
something about yourself.

00:11:49.811 --> 00:11:52.680
You have to start answering
some questions about yourself,

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:55.040
liking some people,
and uploading

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:58.030
a photo-- a lot of things to
do before you can actually

00:11:58.030 --> 00:11:59.480
use the app.

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:03.090
They redesigned their onboarding
to make it more gradual

00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:04.320
and step by step.

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.190
And I'll show you
what I mean exactly.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:08.250
First of all, this is
what they had before.

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:10.890
They required you to write
an essay about yourself,

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:14.110
upload a photo,
answer some questions,

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:17.170
and like some people all
together in the same section

00:12:17.170 --> 00:12:19.700
of the app and with a
series of modal windows

00:12:19.700 --> 00:12:20.840
with no clear sequencing.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:23.592
So the user felt a bit
overwhelmed and like, oh, wow,

00:12:23.592 --> 00:12:26.050
there's a lot of things that
I have to do before I can even

00:12:26.050 --> 00:12:27.030
use this app.

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:28.720
And if you see on
the right, that's

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:30.150
just answering the questions.

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:32.070
Even when you go in
one of the tasks,

00:12:32.070 --> 00:12:33.880
it feels quite
overwhelming because you

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:36.440
have to do-- it's
not that engaging

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:38.810
and there's a lot of things
you have to go through.

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:41.220
So this is how it looks
after the redesign.

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:44.200
The first thing you see
when you download the app

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:47.090
is five questions
about yourself.

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:48.680
It's very easy to
go through them.

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:49.790
Right, yes.

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:51.180
You swipe right, it's yes.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:52.350
Swipe left, it's no.

00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:53.930
Once you finish
that, then you're

00:12:53.930 --> 00:12:56.520
