00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:58.420
If you want, you can skip this.

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:00.700
So you can enjoy the
app even if you don't

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:02.160
want to upload a photo now.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.790
But that's the only thing
you need to care about.

00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:07.580
After that, then you can
start enjoying the app.

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:10.010
And you are also
reminded of other things

00:13:10.010 --> 00:13:12.570
that you should be doing in
order to fully experience

00:13:12.570 --> 00:13:14.880
the app, but it's
just a call to action,

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:16.557
and you can do it
whenever you want.

00:13:16.557 --> 00:13:17.890
And again, this is step by step.

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:21.070
Once you do this, then they push
you another other action to do.

00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:25.810
So it goes from a very
low engagement, very easy

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:29.520
to go to tasks, to a bit more
complex once you actually

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:31.830
start enjoying the app.

00:13:31.830 --> 00:13:33.110
All right.

00:13:33.110 --> 00:13:36.560
So now, users have
decided to stick around.

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:39.220
You've done a great job of
onboarding and communicating

00:13:39.220 --> 00:13:40.470
that sense of progression.

00:13:40.470 --> 00:13:42.780
Well, let's talk about
how you can monetize them.

00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:46.550
I want to talk about
how games look at this.

00:13:46.550 --> 00:13:49.930
Even the most successful
games, no matter

00:13:49.930 --> 00:13:52.830
what you do a big
percentage of users

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:54.680
will never spend a
dime in that game,

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:58.400
and games developers
are cognizant of that.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:01.816
The key thing there is
identifying as soon as possible

00:14:01.816 --> 00:14:03.440
the users that are
more likely to spend

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:05.050
and start targeting them.

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:08.360
And even then, once you identify
the people that are actually

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:10.840
going to spend, understanding
how much they are

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:14.350
willing to spend
is really powerful

00:14:14.350 --> 00:14:17.320
because different users will
have different propensity

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:20.350
to buy-- and targeting them
with a different experience

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:22.450
or different offers
is where you can

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:27.910
optimize much more than applying
a one size fits all approach.

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:30.405
I want to show you who
does a great job of this.

00:14:30.405 --> 00:14:33.450
This is Space Ape, a
successful game developer.

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:36.620
Their games are Samurai
Siege and Rival Kingdom.

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:40.260
What they do here is
they segment users

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:44.430
based on the first
seven day behavior.

00:14:44.430 --> 00:14:46.510
And they calculate, they
predict the lifetime

00:14:46.510 --> 00:14:50.190
value of each user based on the
way they engage with the game.

00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:53.380
And also they tag them with
different spend patterns

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:56.500
the way they spend and buy
things within the game.

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:58.260
And then they start
targeting these users

00:14:58.260 --> 00:14:59.740
with different offers.

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:02.322
Let me show how it works.

00:15:02.322 --> 00:15:03.280
Here are all the users.

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:05.980
They're hitting
Space Ape servers.

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:08.680
Space Ape starts analyzing
them, and then they're

00:15:08.680 --> 00:15:10.190
assigned to a segment.

00:15:10.190 --> 00:15:11.740
Here they have five segments.

00:15:11.740 --> 00:15:14.300
I want to show you
just two as an example.

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:17.535
One is predicted to have
a medium lifetime value,

00:15:17.535 --> 00:15:18.910
but the pattern
here is that they

00:15:18.910 --> 00:15:24.650
spend a lot in one single
chance, in one single purchase,

00:15:24.650 --> 00:15:28.880
and then they tend not to
spend too much too often.

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:31.790
The other group is higher
actually lifetime value.

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:33.660
But in a single spend
they spend less,

00:15:33.660 --> 00:15:36.840
even if they are predicting
that over time these users are

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:38.720
spending more-- in
a single spend point

00:15:38.720 --> 00:15:42.430
they tend to spend less but
the frequency will be higher.

00:15:42.430 --> 00:15:44.640
So then they expose them
to different offers,

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:47.810
different bundles of items--
where the medium lifetime

00:15:47.810 --> 00:15:50.360
value with a high single
spend point and low

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:54.470
spend frequency sees a very
big bundle with lots of stuff

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:56.000
in it, quite expensive.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.680
But it's just buy it once and
probably you never come back.

00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:01.400
You're going to use it
for the rest of the game.

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:04.990
While the medium spend
point sees a smaller

00:16:04.990 --> 00:16:07.570
a bundle, cheaper,
but probably you're

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:10.050
going to come back and buy more.

00:16:10.050 --> 00:16:11.730
So that's very powerful.

00:16:11.730 --> 00:16:14.270
And if you want to
extrapolate a rule for it

00:16:14.270 --> 00:16:16.370
from for the apps
world is you first,

00:16:16.370 --> 00:16:19.280
though, have to realize that
different users are going

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:21.240
to want something
different from your app--

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.220
and especially they will
have a different value

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:25.880
perception and a different
propensity to spend.

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:28.680
And if you can identify
them and target them

00:16:28.680 --> 00:16:33.019
with a different offer that is
more customized around that,

00:16:33.019 --> 00:16:35.310
that's where you can optimize
your conversion much more

00:16:35.310 --> 00:16:35.809
effectively.

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:43.620
A tool that you can use to
start learning about your users

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:46.130
and how the different
segments behave and start

00:16:46.130 --> 00:16:48.130
thinking about what
you can actually

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:51.410
do to tailor their experience
is again Google Analytics.

00:16:51.410 --> 00:16:53.460
This is the segment
builder in Analytics.

00:16:53.460 --> 00:16:57.420
It lets you create segments
with lots of options.

00:16:57.420 --> 00:16:59.720
I want to show you
just the behavior

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:01.130
category of those options.

00:17:01.130 --> 00:17:04.660
You have sessions, days
since last session,

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:06.980
transactions, and
session duration--

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:09.640
so you can create a segment
based on that for example.

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:13.210
And here we have two groups--
one is highly engaged people,

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:15.430
and the other one is
less engaged users.

00:17:15.430 --> 00:17:18.650
And those segments
will then be exposed

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:21.480
in pretty much every report
that is in Google Analytics.

00:17:21.480 --> 00:17:23.470
So, for example, this
is the revenue report,

00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:25.589
and you see, instead of
one line for revenues

00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:28.030
you see revenues for highly
engaged users and revenues

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:29.510
for less engaged users.

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:31.760
So you can really start
understanding how they behave

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:36.190
and what is bringing
you each segment.

00:17:36.190 --> 00:17:39.700
Who does a great job in the apps
world targeting different users

00:17:39.700 --> 00:17:41.760
with different value
proposition is Wish.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:42.910
It's an e-commerce app.

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:44.750
And very simply,
they have a group

00:17:44.750 --> 00:17:47.550
of people that are less engaged
and one is more engaged.

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:49.910
To the less engaged
people, the feed

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:51.330
of products that
they recommend is

00:17:51.330 --> 00:17:53.740
less expensive because it
requires less commitment

00:17:53.740 --> 00:17:57.140
and less engagement to actually
think of purchasing them.

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:01.600
Well, once they see more
engagement and some conversion,

00:18:01.600 --> 00:18:04.210
they start recommending
more expensive products.

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:07.640
So quite simple, but it lead
to 10% better conversion just

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:10.760
by doing that.

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:11.260
All right.

00:18:11.260 --> 00:18:16.790
The last one I want to
show is selling umbrellas

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:17.990
where and when it rains.

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:21.880
This is how you sell products
instead of what you sell.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:24.600
If you look at this
screenshot from Pretty Simple,

00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:29.080
another game developer--
Pretty Simple Games--

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:31.480
they made an art, not only
a science, out of this.

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:34.760
And I want to show
you an example of how

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:37.184
this can be really optimized.

00:18:37.184 --> 00:18:38.850
Playdots-- again,
they are the developer

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:42.670
we talked about before
with the progression chart,

00:18:42.670 --> 00:18:45.740
they also redesigned
their purchase flow

00:18:45.740 --> 00:18:48.170
across the whole game.

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:51.070
And overall they achieve
10% better revenue

00:18:51.070 --> 00:18:54.701
per active user, which is
a big number because it's

00:18:54.701 --> 00:18:56.950
for all users, including the
ones that are not paying.

00:18:56.950 --> 00:19:01.280
So overall, 10% revenue per
user is quite an achievement.

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:05.790
And I'll show you a couple
of examples of what they did.

00:19:05.790 --> 00:19:10.100
The first one is, before
you start a level,

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:13.070
you see a card that shows you
some stats of what you have,

00:19:13.070 --> 00:19:15.100
and it prompts you to
buy things that you

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:16.710
might need in that level.

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:18.380
It's not the whole
store, it just

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:20.970
prompts you to buy specific
things-- in this case

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:24.690
it's boxes-- that you might
need in that specific level.

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:27.590
And similarly, when
you die in a level--

00:19:27.590 --> 00:19:31.670
basically you run out of
moves-- the first thing

00:19:31.670 --> 00:19:34.820
you see is a button that
lets you buy extra moves that

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:36.570
lets you finish that level.

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:38.700
Instead of starting
over again and just

00:19:38.700 --> 00:19:40.460
going back to the
store and buying those,

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:43.720
you can buy them now and
keep playing the level.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:47.150
By doing this, they obtained
6% more paying users

00:19:47.150 --> 00:19:50.924
just by adding these
two call to actions.

00:19:50.924 --> 00:19:53.090
The other thing they did,
they moved some products--

00:19:53.090 --> 00:19:56.050
some in-app products--
within the game experience.

00:19:56.050 --> 00:20:01.510
So instead of having them
exposed in the store only,

00:20:01.510 --> 00:20:05.160
they also highlight them
on the bottom of the game.

00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:07.204
So whenever you want
while you're playing,

00:20:07.204 --> 00:20:08.120
you can purchase them.

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:09.020
And it's one tap.

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:12.960
This led to 5% better ARPU.

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:17.390
Overall, if we want to simplify
and generalize this for apps,

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:20.560
it's about selling umbrellas
where and when it rains.

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:26.180
It's not only making purchasing
accessible and easy for users

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:31.030
so that it's as close as
possible to their experiences--

00:20:31.030 --> 00:20:32.820
one tap away or two taps away.

00:20:32.820 --> 00:20:36.230
But also triggering
some call to actions

00:20:36.230 --> 00:20:39.400
when and where it's very
relevant, that specific product

00:20:39.400 --> 00:20:41.342
that you're selling.

00:20:41.342 --> 00:20:45.230
Who does a great job at this
in the apps world is TomTom.

00:20:45.230 --> 00:20:47.770
They recently moved from
premium to freemium,

00:20:47.770 --> 00:20:51.880
and they sold 2.4 times
more paying users.

00:20:51.880 --> 00:20:55.120
And that's because they
moved in the right way.

00:20:55.120 --> 00:20:57.370
They actually thought
about their business model

00:20:57.370 --> 00:21:00.770
and how they could
sell upgrade to premium

00:21:00.770 --> 00:21:01.990
in a very clever way.

00:21:01.990 --> 00:21:03.000
I want to show you how.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:07.460
The model is that you have
75 kilometers for free.

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:09.220
You can use the app
for 75 kilometers

00:21:09.220 --> 00:21:10.760
and you don't have to pay.

00:21:10.760 --> 00:21:13.720
It's a real metering model.

00:21:13.720 --> 00:21:15.150
It's real meters.

00:21:15.150 --> 00:21:19.150
And then you can upgrade
to one year or three year

00:21:19.150 --> 00:21:20.470
subscriptions.

00:21:20.470 --> 00:21:22.550
And the first thing
they did is that they

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:25.320
made that upgrade bottom
always available there.

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:26.750
It's on the bottom of the app.

00:21:26.750 --> 00:21:28.458
Wherever you are in
the app you see that.

00:21:28.458 --> 00:21:30.640
It's one tap away--
you can upgrade.

00:21:30.640 --> 00:21:33.860
And you also see the countdown--
how many kilometres for free

00:21:33.860 --> 00:21:34.760
you still have.

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:37.390
So 75, 74, 73-- you
see the progression

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:40.487
and you know when you
need to hit that button.

00:21:40.487 --> 00:21:43.070
The other thing they did-- very
similarly to the other example

00:21:43.070 --> 00:21:45.900
I showed you-- they
trigger some call to action

00:21:45.900 --> 00:21:47.170
when it's quite relevant.

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:49.411
For example, if you
start a new trip,

00:21:49.411 --> 00:21:50.910
they know that
you're probably going

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:53.390
to run out of kilometres
because that trip is quite long

00:21:53.390 --> 00:21:55.830
and you only have 40
kilometers, for example.

00:21:55.830 --> 00:21:58.475
They trigger a call
to action that says

00:21:58.475 --> 00:21:59.860
do you want to upgrade now.

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:01.480
It's better,
probably, because you

00:22:01.480 --> 00:22:03.210
don't want to upgrade
when you're driving

00:22:03.210 --> 00:22:05.590
or you might not have a
connection or you're abroad.

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:11.300
So things like that they also
trigger a call to action when

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:13.030
you're actually running
out of kilometers

00:22:13.030 --> 00:22:15.210
and when you run
out of kilometres.

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:19.650
But the point here is that it's
relevant and it's easy to do it

00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:22.340
and I understand why
I should purchase

00:22:22.340 --> 00:22:24.261
the upgrade in this moment.

00:22:24.261 --> 00:22:24.760
All right.

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:27.790
To wrap up, the
rules are three-- one

00:22:27.790 --> 00:22:31.800
is addressing the onboarding
as an engagement cliff.

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:37.080
And so, start by analyzing your
day one to day seven retention

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:38.500
figures in Analytics.

00:22:38.500 --> 00:22:40.540
And thinking about
activation moments that

00:22:40.540 --> 00:22:42.480
are gradually more
invested for the user,

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:44.400
and how you can introduce
them in the app.

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:47.110
The second one is embracing
your apps multiple personality

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:49.400
disorder-- so understanding
that different users want

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.066
different things and
you can target them

00:22:51.066 --> 00:22:54.780
with different ways, especially
when it comes to in-app offers

00:22:54.780 --> 00:22:56.900
and propensity to buy.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:23:00.450
And the third one is about
not only what you sell,

00:23:00.450 --> 00:23:01.870
but how you sell it.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:03.950
And we say that it's
like selling umbrellas

00:23:03.950 --> 00:23:05.160
where and when it rains.

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:09.550
Make it easy for people to
buy, but also very relevant,

00:23:09.550 --> 00:23:11.310
and triggering
call to action when

00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:16.520
you think the most chances are
that the user will convert.

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:20.410
So, thank you for
listening today.

